	<li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="comment-10102" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-10102" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/deeca582aa1e51adcbdb91001aa500c2?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name"><a itemprop='url' href='http://digitalstrategyworks.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Tony Zeoli</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2010/wordpress-3-0-multisite-domain-mapping-tutorial/comment-page-9/#comment-10102">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2011-11-05T16:57:06+00:00">November 5, 2011 at 4:57 pm</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>Hey Carla:</p>
<p>You need to use a Google XML sitemap plugin that works with multi-site networks, like this one: <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/bwp-google-xml-sitemaps/" rel="nofollow">http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/bwp-google-xml-sitemaps/</a></p>
<p>It will give you you a separate site map for each URL, then you&#8217;ll have to register them with Google Webmaster Tools, so Google knows the sitemap URL to crawl for each site in the network.</p>
</div>

	<div class="reply">
	<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/wordpress-3-0-multisite-domain-mapping-tutorial/comment-page-9/?replytocom=10102#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-10102", "10102", "respond", "166")'>Reply to this comment</a>	</div>
